{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "6682bd10ba0e94a3c4025a4c", "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 1, "category": null, "approximateTimeRequired": 60, "imageBaseUrl": null, "helperText": null, "source": "", "questionLabels": [], "question": {"text": "A species having carbon with sextet of electrons and can act as electrophile is called", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "IzAje", "text": "carbon free radical", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "DO0tv", "text": "carbanion", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}, {"id": "S4KNC", "text": "carbocation", "image": null, "isCorrect": true}, {"id": "et0fm", "text": "pentavalent carbon", "image": null, "isCorrect": false}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "<p>A\u00a0carbocation\u00a0is a molecule in which a carbon atom has a positive charge and three bonds. We can say that, basically, they are carbon cations. Formerly, it was known as carbonium ion. Carbocation today is defined as any even-electron cation that possesses a significant positive charge on the carbon atom.</p><p>The carbon cations are very reactive and unstable due to an incomplete octet. In simple words, carbocations do not have eight electrons; therefore, they do not satisfy the octet rule.</p><p>In carbocation, the hybridisation of carbon\u00a0will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>\u00a0and its shape is trigonal planar. There is also a vacant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mo>-</mo></math> orbital which indicates its electron-deficient nature. The carbon has <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> electrons in its valence shell. Due to this, it is an electron-deficient species, also known as an electrophile.</p><p><img src=\"https://cdn-question-pool.getmarks.app/pyq/jee_main/a9921478-f91f-43f0-a083-c24ae9973c5e.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 222px;\"/></p><p>Six electron species</p>", "image": null}, "videoSolution": null, "bucket": "Easy Ques (Board Level)", "concepts": [], "masterId": "MOGJMPYQ83055233", "subject": "Chemistry", "subjects": ["615d70bd9948bc1b21da2b1f"], "chapters": ["615d6fee2b295b085ab6ebb6"], "topics": [], "previousYearPapers": [{"_id": "65c4c0c11d30997d3436bb04", "title": "JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)", "isVisible": true}], "numericalLowerLimit": null, "numericalUpperLimit": null, "classes": [], "microConcepts": [], "exams": ["615d76b2c52ffa3c944600df"], "isRemoved": false, "cpyqbSubjects": ["615f0cf69476412f48314dac", "616057040283de43c87e3e16", "61bb58281213731910ea0b71", "6160579d0283de43c87e3e1f", "61964f94a5a526011886801e", "61c055f6e8ce0dc8a5c62d34", "61a8a2cce8ce0dc8a5c62d2e", "6160577e0283de43c87e3e1c", "616057210283de43c87e3e19", "629105adee9e3ae00d63352c", "62962075e7f8e9ac4daeafd8", "629f385f263330a77be9fa7e", "629f39e4ac11b26562e0625c", "61964ff3a5a5260118868022", "64d50c263df7f4a7f3017f70", "66b79b89d4b564dfab4f94d0", "678ea9a09cc79e5f592bdc12", "67fa602f4468eb1307ceb0ae", "6807d350647479b8e869647a"], "cpyqbChapters": ["616024b351f722cb35d69768", "616024b5635828cf45c2c86f", "616024b6d2493860e013037f", "616024b40048a39f6f22a9ec", "61964ca31c4aef0c16be05e7", "61bb821aa62a5cabef1ec237", "61c0899ad936cdbbae41cf5a", "61e7bd763d4a5821d8e1c282", "61964ca3ddb2ce8ed14e412e", "616024b5faac2d55bcb45537", "629f38ff4a0adb3149fa6f8d", "629109dc4f253f21a30897e2", "6296211811ee9cfa06f2361e", "629f3a85233d1ae59e12c20e", "64eb06c83118f713ecfef0c5", "66d5853da75f05ee8564f58b", "67921d721d5b5072da5e9b25", "67fdff53378e1624ea7b6a3a", "68091fe13a10446a207fdbe1"], "cpyqbExams": ["615f0e999476412f48314daf", "616059af0283de43c87e3e23"]}}